Telco customers churn analysis¶

This comprehensive analysis of Telco customer churn provides an in-depth data overview, including a churn distribution, correlation analysis of key features, a performance comparison of three classifiers, and an interactive prediction tool within one data app constructed using Holoviz Panel.

Configurations¶

Descriptive analysis¶

1. Overall churn

The initial step of the descriptive analysis was to explore the overall customer churn across the entire data frame.A donut chart was employed to represent this visually.

The chart indicated that the percentage of customers who churned during the given period was less than 30%.

A correlation threshold of 0.18 revealed that the following features had the most significant influence on customer churn:

  • Contract type (monthly: 0.4 and two year: -0.3)
  • Online security(no security: 0.34 and no internet: -0.23)
  • Tech support(no support: 0.34)
  • Internet service (fiber optic: 0.31)
  • Payment method (electronic check: 0.3)
  • Paperless billing (yes: 0.19 and no: -0.19)
  • Online backup (no backup: 0.27 and no internet: -0.23)
  • Device protection (no protection: 0.25 and no internet: -0.23)
  • Streaming TV (no internet: -0.23)
  • Streaming Movies (no internet: -0.23)
  • Tenure (-0.35)
  • Monthly charges (0.19)
  • Total charges (-0.2)

Out of 13 features 10 of them were categorical and 3 numeric which were further explored separately.

Categorical features were then individually explored in relation to churn in order to visually demonstrate their impact.

Analysis of the plots revealed that:

  • customers with monthly contract type displayed a significantly higher churn rate compared to those with two year contracts
  • surprisingly, customers whose internet was supplied via fiber optic experienced a higher churn rate
  • the electronic check payment method had a signigficant negative influence on customer retention
  • paperless billing, when present, had an impact on cutomer churn
  • a noticeable trend was observed among the features related to technical services provided to customers with internet access (tech support, online security, online backup, device protection and streaming services). It was found that customer churn was significantly higher when those services were absent, whereas the lack of internet connection (and therefore the lack of those services) did not have a significant impact on churn.

4. The most correlated numeric features

The two-way approach was chosen for the visualisation of the numeric features. The distribution of churn was visualised for each feature, followed by plotting the features against each other.

#Saving figure locally
plt.savefig('NumFeats.png');

It was observed that a lower tenure (less than 10 months) had a greater impact on customer churn than a higher tenure (around 70 months), which positively affected customer retention. Monthly charges ranging from 80-100 had a bigger impact on churn, while very low monthly charges had a positive effect on customer retention. Interestingly, it was observed that lower total fees had a considerable effect on both churn and retention, whereas higher fees did not increase the churn rate as would be expected based on the tendency with the monthly charges. It can be inferred that total charges are proportional to the tenure, as evidenced by the last plot (lower right).

2. Predictive analysis¶

The next step was to construct a prediction model utilizing existing classifiers from the sklearn library.

Compare three classifiers¶

In this analysis, three classifiers were evaluated: Decision Tree, Random Forest and AdaBoost. The models were fitted on the training data derived from the data frame and their performance was visualised using a confusion matrix plot.

In [13]:
#Preparing data for classification
X = df.drop(['Churn','customerID'],axis=1)
X = pd.get_dummies(X,drop_first=True)
y = df['Churn']

#Train/test split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.1, random_state=101)

#Decision Tree (model fitting and prediction)
dt = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=6)
dt.fit(X_train,y_train)
dt_preds = dt.predict(X_test)

#Random Forest (model fitting and prediction)
rf = RandomForestClassifier(max_depth=6)
rf.fit(X_train,y_train)
rf_preds = rf.predict(X_test)

#Ada Boost (model fitting and prediction)
ada = AdaBoostClassifier()
ada.fit(X_train,y_train)
ada_preds = ada.predict(X_test)

#Figure
fig,axes = plt.subplots(nrows=3,ncols=1,figsize=(3,5))

#Building confusion matrix for Decision Tree
cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, dt_preds, labels=dt.classes_)
disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=cm, display_labels=dt.classes_)
cmap = matplotlib.colors.LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list('', ['white',green])
disp.plot(cmap=cmap,ax=axes[0])
axes[0].set_title('DecisionTree',fontweight='bold',fontsize=12,rotation='vertical',x=-0.75,y=-0.05)
axes[0].xaxis.label.set_visible(False)
axes[0].grid(False)

#Building confusion matrix for Random Forest
cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, rf_preds, labels=rf.classes_)
disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=cm, display_labels=rf.classes_)
cmap = matplotlib.colors.LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list('', ['white',blue])
disp.plot(cmap=cmap,ax=axes[1])
axes[1].set_title('RandomForest',fontweight='bold',fontsize=12,rotation='vertical',x=-0.75,y=-0.05)
axes[1].xaxis.label.set_visible(False)
axes[1].grid(False)

#Building confusion matrix for Ada Boost
cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, ada_preds, labels=ada.classes_)
disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=cm, display_labels=ada.classes_)
cmap = matplotlib.colors.LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list('', ['white',red])
disp.plot(cmap=cmap,ax=axes[2])
axes[2].set_title('AdaBoost',fontweight='bold',fontsize=12,rotation='vertical',x=-0.75,y=0.05)
axes[2].grid(False)

#Tight layout
plt.tight_layout()

#Saving figure locally
plt.savefig('ConfMatrix.png',bbox_inches='tight');

The test revealed that the Decision Tree algorithm was most accurate in predicting churn cases, while Random Forest had the best accuracy in predicting customer retention. Therefore, it was determined that all three algorithms should be maintained in the future prediction tool to provide a balanced, objective assessment.

3. Building the dashboard¶

The final step was to create a dashboard to demonstrate the analysis performed with the data set as well as provide an intercative prediction tool for the customer churn. For that purpose, the Holoviz Panel library was employed, enabling the creation of input widgets that dynamically affect the results of the prediction algorithm. The prediction results were then visualized in the form of a donut chart, which allowed for the representation of the churn prediction ratio across all three classifiers.

Plotting function¶

In [15]:
#Takes in widgets values > returns a donut chart with the prediction results from all three classifiers
def pred(gender,SeniorCitizen,Partner,Dependents,tenure,PhoneService,MultipleLines,InternetService,
         OnlineSecurity,OnlineBackup,DeviceProtection,TechSupport,StreamingTV,StreamingMovies,Contract,
         PaperlessBilling,PaymentMethod,MonthlyCharges,TotalCharges):
    
    #Read data
    df = pd.read_csv('Telco-Customer-Churn-edited.csv')
    
    #Input df from the widget values
    input_df = pd.DataFrame({'gender':gender,'SeniorCitizen':SeniorCitizen,'Partner':Partner,'Dependents':Dependents,
                            'tenure':int(tenure),'PhoneService':PhoneService,'MultipleLines':MultipleLines,
                            'InternetService':InternetService,'OnlineSecurity':OnlineSecurity,'OnlineBackup':OnlineBackup,
                            'DeviceProtection':DeviceProtection,'TechSupport':TechSupport,
                            'StreamingTV':StreamingTV,'StreamingMovies':StreamingMovies,'Contract':Contract,
                            'PaperlessBilling':PaperlessBilling,'PaymentMethod':PaymentMethod,
                            'MonthlyCharges':float(MonthlyCharges),'TotalCharges':float(TotalCharges)},index=[0])
    
    #Concatenated df
    df = pd.concat([df,input_df])
    
    #Preparing data for classification
    X = df.drop(['Churn','customerID'],axis=1)
    X = pd.get_dummies(X,drop_first=True)
    X_train = X.iloc[:-1]
    X_test = X.iloc[[-1]]
    y_train = df.iloc[:-1,-1]
    
    #Decision Tree fitting
    dt = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=6)
    dt.fit(X_train,y_train)

    #Random Forest fitting
    rf = RandomForestClassifier(max_depth=6)
    rf.fit(X_train,y_train)

    #Ada Boost fitting
    ada = AdaBoostClassifier()
    ada.fit(X_train,y_train)

    #Prediction 
    dt_pred = dt.predict(X_test)
    rf_pred = rf.predict(X_test)
    ada_pred = ada.predict(X_test)
    
    #Values  and labels for the donut plot
    preds = [dt_pred,rf_pred,ada_pred]
    no = []
    yes = []
    
    #Assigning labels
    for i in preds:
        if i == 'No':
            no.append(i)
        else:
            yes.append(i)
    values = [len(no),len(yes)]
    if values[0]==3:      
        labels = ['No','']
    elif values[0]==0:
        labels = ['','Yes']
    else:
        labels = ['No','Yes']
        
    #Figure
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(2.7,2.7))
    
    #Pie plot
    plt.pie(values,labels=labels,colors=[blue,red],labeldistance=1.2,
            textprops={'fontsize':12,'fontweight':'bold','va':'center'},
            wedgeprops={'linewidth':3,'edgecolor':background})
    
    #Circle patch
    my_circle1 = plt.Circle((0,0), 0.7, color=background)
    plt.gca().add_artist(my_circle1)
    
    #Closing the figure
    plt.close(fig)
 
    return fig
